profiles.name: Seppo Pakonen
profiles.biography:
Seppo Pakonen is from Oulu, Finland. He takes strong influences from American 90s hip-hop, grunge, classic rock, and Finnish alternative rock. When he was younger, he listened to a lot of Finnish hip-hop and EDM.

He started making music in 1999 with the music program eJay Dance. He made his first completely own composition in 2001 with the Fruity Loops program. He moved into professional music production in 2003 when he started using Steinberg Cubase. He has played electric guitar in 3 metal bands and gigged locally a bit.

However, the biggest listens he has come from hip-hop, which is closest to his heart.

years.keywords: Daycare, Detached houses, Sammaloja, Kiiminki, Befriended, Local children, Important, Everyday things, Life, Didn't hear, Home
years.native_text:
Olin päivähoidossa eri omakotitaloissa eripuolella Sammaloja, Kiiminki aluetta. Ystävystyin näissä paikoissa paikallisten samanikäisten lasten kanssa.
Muistan kuinka naiset kertoivat tärkeitä arkisia asioita elämästä, mitä en kotona kuullut.
years.text:
I was in daycare in different detached houses in different parts of Sammaloja, Kiiminki area. I befriended local children of the same age in these places.
I remember how the women told important everyday things about life that I didn't hear at home.

years.keywords: daycare center, Viitantie, Kiiminki, big building, large hall, second floor, two sections, mother's workplace, occasional visits, nap time, 40-50 children, playtime, talk, yard, summer, Sammaloja, Nielukuja, ladies' club, children's playground, snacks
years.native_text:
Olin päiväkodissa Viitantie:llä Kiimingissä. 
Rakennus oli silloin todella iso. Siinä oli iso sali, jossa oli toinen kerros.
Päiväkoti oli jaettu kahteen osastoon, ja äitini oli töissä toisella osastolla.
Näin äitiäni siellä silloin tällöin ja juttelin hänen kanssaan.
Joskus hän oli pihalla vahtimassa meitä ja joskus hän laittoi meidät päiväunille.
Päiväkodissa oli 40-50 lasta muistaakseni.
Pihalla oli paljon kenen kanssa leikkiä ja jutellakkin vähän.

Kesäaikana Sammalojalla Nielukujan päässä lasten leikkikentällä oli kerhon tätejä, joiden luo menimme päiväsaikaan leikkimään mudien lasten kanssa.
Saimme siellä myös eväitä.
years.text:
I was in a daycare center on Viitantie in Kiiminki.
The building was really big at the time. There was a large hall with a second floor.
The daycare center was divided into two sections, and my mother worked in the other section.
I would see my mother there occasionally and talk to her.
Sometimes she would watch us in the yard and other times she would put us down for nap time.
There were 40-50 children in the daycare center, if I remember correctly.
There were plenty of kids to play and talk with in the yard.

During the summer at Sammaloja on the end of Nielukuja, there would be some ladies from a club at the children's playground during the day, where we would go to play with the other kids.
We also got some snacks there.

years.keywords: First grade, Kiiminkijoki elementary school, Friends, Nearby area, Playground, Daycare, Learning, Computers, Windows PC, Instruction, Games, "Save Henrietta", Math game, Inspired, Visiting, Homes
years.native_text:
Menin Kiiminkijoen ala-asteen ensimmäiselle luokalle syyskuussa.
Luokallani oli paljon tuttuja kavereita lähialueeltani, leikkikentiltä ja päivähoidosta.

Meillä alkoi ATK-opetus heti ensimmäisellä luokalla.
Opiskelimme Windows PC:eiden käyttämistä 1 tunnin viikossa.
Koneilla oli mielenkiintoisia pelejä, kuten "Pelastakaa Henrietta" matematiikkapeli.
ATK-Tunnit inspiroivat minua ja kavereitani vierailemaan toisten kotona käyttämässä tietokoneita.
years.text:
I started the first grade at Kiiminkijoki elementary school in September.
I had many familiar friends in my class from the nearby area, from playgrounds and from daycare.

We started learning about computers right away in first grade.
We had 1 hour of Windows PC instruction per week.
The computers had interesting games, like "Save Henrietta" math game.
The computer classes inspired me and my friends to visit each other's homes to use computers.

years.keywords: Second grade, Kiiminkijoki lower level school, Computer classes, PE classes, Fun activities, Skiing, Nearby river, Stairs, Winter, Skiing competition, Second place, Classmates, Sports, Extracurricular activities, Friends, Not joining
years.native_text:
Toinen luokka, Kiiminkijoen ala-asteella.
ATK-Tunnit jatkuivat.
Tiistai oli todella lyhyt päivä, mikä oli mukavaa.
Liikuntatunneilla teimme kaikkea hauskaa, kuten hiihdimme viereisellä joella.
Joelle meni silloin portaat koulun pihalta.
Talvella oli hiihtokilpailut, jossa tulin toiseksi.
Leikimme paljon luokkavareiden kanssa ja urheilimmekin yhdessä.
Muut kaverit tosin alkoivat käydä harrastuksissa.
Minä taisin aloittaa klassisen kitaran soittamisen tänä vuonna.
Kävin ehkä puoli vuotta kitaratunneilla.
years.text:
Second grade, at Kiiminki Elementary.
The computer lessons continued.
Tuesday was a really short day, which was nice.
During gym class, we did all sorts of fun things, like cross-country skiing on the nearby river.
There were stairs leading down to the river from the school yard.
In the winter, there were skiing competitions where I came in second place.
We played a lot with my classmates and also did sports together.
Although some of my friends started joining clubs.
I think I started playing classical guitar this year.
I took guitar lessons for about six months.

years.keywords: Third grade, Kiiminkijoki lower elementary school, Limu-discos, Excitement, Single mother, Emotional support, Partner dancing, Peer pressure, Thigh pocket trinkets, Alone, Useless mother, Slow dances, Childhood friend, Hanna, Fun, Male figure, Sexual harassment, Deep scars, Serious, Sexual abuse, Social support, Ostracized, Discrimination, Exponentially worsen, Recesses, Alone
years.native_text:
Kolmas luokka Kiiminkijoen ala-asteella.
Limu-diskot alkoivat meille kolmasluokkalaisille.
Tunsin syvää jännitystä niitä kohtaan, koska asuin surullisen yksinhuoltaja-äidin kanssa, eikä paritanssiin tullut mitään tunnetason tukea.
Vertaispaineen myötä menin limudiskoon.
Minulle hankittiin uudenlaiset reisitaskuhoudut sinne.
Olin täysin yksin limudiskossa, ilman mitään ymmärrystä mitä siellä pitäisi tehdä tai mitä ihmiset yleensä tekee, kiitos hyödyttömän äitini.
Luokkakaverini painostivat minut tanssimaan lapsuudenkaverini Hannan kanssa hitaita.
Tanssiminen oli mukavaa.
Tunsin jälkeenpäin oloni todella ahdistuneeksi, koska kotona ei ollut ketään miespuolista, joka olisi ymmärtänyt minua.
Jälkeenpäin voi sanoa, että kyseessä oli vakava seksuaalinen ahdistelu, joka jätti syvät arvet, vaikka ulkopuolisille tämä ei kuulosta miltään välttämättä.
En saattanut mennä limudiskoon enää uudestaan, mikä erotti minua muista luokkakavereista, ja he lopulta alkoivat syrjimään minua.
Jouduin käytännössä syrjityksiä koulussa tapahtuneen seksuaalisen hyväksikäytön takia, jolle ei annettu sosiaalista tukea, mikä alkoi pahentaa tilannettani eksponentiaalisesti.
Minua ei otettu mukaan jalkapallon pelaamiseen, minua kohdeltiin oudolta, ja vietin välitunnit täysin yksin.
Pahinta oli, että myöhemmin muut tekivät myös tanssiparini elämästä hankalaa, vaikka vastuu oli meidän painostajilla, opettajilla ja koko yhteisöllä.
years.text:
Third grade at Kiiminkijoki primary school.
The soda discos started for us third graders.
I felt deep nerves towards them, because I lived with my sad single mother, and there was no emotional support for dancing.
Due to peer pressure, I went to the soda disco.
I was given new thigh pocket gadgets to wear there.
I was completely alone at the soda disco, without any understanding of what I should do there or what people usually do, thanks to my useless mother.
My classmates pressured me to dance slow dances with my childhood friend Hanna.
The dancing was nice.
Afterwards, I felt really anxious, because there was no male figure at home who would have understood me.
In hindsight, it can be said that it was a serious case of sexual harassment, which left deep scars, even though to outsiders this may not sound like anything significant.
I couldn't go to the soda disco anymore, which separated me from the other classmates, and they eventually started to discriminate against me.
I was practically marginalized in school because of the sexual abuse that had occurred, for which I was not given any social support, which began to worsen my situation exponentially.
I wasn't invited to play soccer, I was treated strangely, and I spent recesses completely alone.
The worst part was that later on, others also made my dance partner's life difficult, even though the responsibility lay with our harassers, teachers, and the whole community.

years.keywords: Fourth grade, Kiiminkijoki Elementary School, Ostracized, Lonely, Sexual harassment, Strangeness, Negativity, Exclusion, Football, Boys, Class, Understanding, Mother, Calling, Explaining, Embarrassment, Psychological turmoil.
years.native_text:
Neljäs luokka Kiiminkijoen ala-asteella.
Olin täysin syrjitty ja yksinäinen, kiitos koulussa tapahtuneen seksuaalisen ahdistelun, mitä leimattiin minun outoudekseni.
Minua kohdeltiin tosi negatiivisesti, eikä minua otettu mukaan pelaamaan jalkapalloa, vaikka kaikki muut luokan pojat pelasivat.
En ymmärtänyt syytä.
Äitini sotki asioitani entisestään soittamalla koululle selittäen kaiken väärin ja nolosti, ja siten myös aiheuttaen vielä pahempaa psykologista sekamelskaa.
years.text:
Fouth grade at Kiiminkijoki Elementary School.
I was completely ostracized and lonely, thanks to the sexual harassment that happened at school, which was labeled as my strangeness.
I was treated really negatively, and I wasn't included in playing football, even though all the other boys in my class played.
I didn't understand the reason.
My mother made things worse by calling the school and explaining everything wrong and embarrassingly, causing even more psychological turmoil.

years.native_text:
Uusi kouluni oli Haukipudas, Kellon ala-aste, Luokka 5C.

Muutin kesällä 2000, kun äitini tapasi uuden miesystävän.
En olisi halunnut jättää Kiimnkiä taakseni ollenkaan, vaikka siellä olikin melko ankeaa.
Tässä koulussa ihmiset olivat hyvin erilaisia Kiiminkiin nähden.
He olivat paljon lapsenmielisempiä ja ystävällisempiä, ja myös vähemmän kilpailullisia, vaikkakin enemmän urheilullisia.
years.text:
My new school was in Haukipudas, Kello's elementary school, Class 5C.

I moved in the summer of 2000 when my mother met a new boyfriend.
I didn't want to leave Kiiminki behind, even though it was quite bleak there.
The people at this school were very different from Kiiminki.
They were much more childish and friendly, and also less competitive, although more athletic.

years.keywords: changed, schools, free will, sister, new school, Haukipudas, visit, Oulu Rudolf Steiner School, content, rootlessness, curiosity, sold, magnificent, regular schools, switch, attend, full school year, Kello Elementary, owed, good friends, grateful.
years.native_text:
Vaihdoin koulua omasta tahdostani.
Siskoni ei viihtynyt uudessa koulussa Haukiputaalta, ja hän kävi tutustumassa Oulun Rudolf Steiner-kouluun.
Minä viihdyin hyvin lukuunottamatta juurettomuuden tuntoa.
Uteliaisuuteni voitti, ja lähdin samana päivänä tutustumaan Steinerkouluun, kuin siskoni.
Olin myyty välittömästi.
Steinerkoulu oli todella mahtava koulu tavallisiin kouluihin verrattuna.
Vaihdoin mielellään sinne samantien.
En ollut kokonaista lukuvuotta Kellon Ala-asteella, mutta en tuntenut olevani velkaa heille.
Sain tästä koulusta kuitenkin hyviä kavereita ylä-asteeni ajaksi.

Steinerluokkani kanssa kävimme pienillä retkillä usein, ja lämpimään aikaan olimme yhden päivän ulkona opiskelemassa eräällä vanhalla huvilalla keskellä luontoa.
years.text:
I switched schools of my own free will.
My sister didn't like her new school in Haukipudas, so she went to check out the Oulu Rudolf Steiner School.
I enjoyed it there, except for feeling a bit rootless.
My curiosity got the best of me, and I decided to go check out the Steiner School on the same day as my sister.
I was sold immediately.
The Steiner School was truly amazing compared to the regular schools.
I was happy to switch there right away.
Even though I didn't spend a full school year at Kello Primary School, I didn't feel like I owed them anything.
But I did make some good friends that I went to middle school with.

My Steiner class often went on small trips, and in the warmer weather we spent a whole day studying at an old villa in the middle of nature.

Huomasin kyllä, että olimme jäljessä äidinkielen ja matematiikan opiskelussa, mutta se en välittänyt siitä.
Opiskelimme isompaa maailmankuvaa, mitä tavallisessa koulussa ei opetettu.
Kävimme paljon mielenkiintoisempia keskusteluja uudessa koulussa.

Vanhat Kiimingin kaverini jo joivat alkoholia ja tupakoivat, kun minä vietin aikaani hyvin vanhoollisessa ympäristössä.
Minua harmitti tyttöjen puute vapaa-ajalla, ja olisin halunnut seurustella.
years.text:
Oulu Steiner School, 7th grade (1st year of upper secondary school).
I really enjoyed my time at the Steiner school.
We did all sorts of interesting things that were not done in regular schools.
I did notice that we were behind in learning Finnish and math, but I didn't mind.
We studied a larger world view, which was not taught in regular schools.
We had much more interesting discussions in the new school.

My old friends from Kiiminki were already drinking and smoking, while I spent my time in a very conservative environment.
I was frustrated by the lack of girls to hang out with during free time, and I wanted to date.

years.native_text:
Tampereen Rudolf Steiner lukion Oulun toimipiste, Oulussa. Lukion 1. luokka.
Vanhat kaverini Haukiputaalta Kellon Kiviniemestä saivat minut vakavasti harkitsemaan Oulun Normaalikoulun Lukiota.
Menin heidän kanssa ilmoittautumiseen, ja vielä rehtorin huoneen edessä mietin, että vaihdanko tänne.
Näin kun kaverini ilmoittautuivat sinne, mutta en tuntenut mitään vetoa, enkä nähnyt etuja.
Olin edelleen Oulun steinerkoulussa, vaikka sekään ei tuntunut täysin hyvältä idealta.
Tiesin, että siellä oleminen tulee olemaan erilaista.
Meille tuli luokalle uusia oppilaita, joiden kanssa tulin toimeen heikommin, kuin aijempien.
Käytännössä kaikki uudet oppilaat olivat olleet valtion koulussa, ja ero alkuperäisten steinerkoululaisten ja uusien oppilaiden välillä oli iso.
Tunsin olevani puoleksi kumpaakin, mutta ilman että kukaan ymmärtää minua.
Huomasin, kuinka positiivisen vaikutuksen 4 steinervuottani olivat tehneet ajatusmaailmaani.
years.text:
The Oulu branch of Tampere Rudolf Steiner High School, located in Oulu. First year of high school.
My old friends from Haukipudas and Kello Kiviniemi made me seriously consider Oulu Normal School's high school program.
I went with them to register, and even in front of the principal's office, I wondered if I should switch here.
I saw my friends register there, but I didn't feel any pull, nor did I see any benefits.
I was still at the Oulu Steiner School, although that didn't feel like a completely good idea either.
I knew being there would be different.
We had new students in our class, and I didn't get along with them as well as I did with the previous ones.
In practice, all the new students had come from state schools, and the difference between the original Steiner students and the new ones was huge.
I felt like I was half of both, but without anyone understanding me.
I noticed how much my four years at the Steiner school had positively influenced my way of thinking.

value.text:
(Education Campus, year 1994, age 5) I was in daycare in different detached houses in different parts of Sammaloja, Kiiminki area. I befriended local children of the same age in these places.
I remember how the women told important everyday things about life that I didn't hear at home.

Growing up in Kiiminki in the mid-1990s, education played a big role in my life. At the age of 6, I attended a daycare center on Viitantie. The building was huge, with a large hall and a second floor. My mother worked in the other section and I would occasionally see her there. During the summer, I would also play with other kids at the nearby playground.

At the age of 7, I started first grade at Kiiminkijoki elementary school. Many of my friends from the playground and daycare also attended the same school. In first grade, we started learning about computers and had one hour of Windows PC instruction per week. We were fascinated by the games, especially "Save Henrietta" math game. This sparked our interest and we would often visit each other's homes to use computers. It was a formative time for my education and love for technology.

During my early childhood in Kiiminki, education had a strong presence in my life. From ages 4 to 5, I attended daycare in different houses around the local area and formed friendships with kids my age. I remember the women at these places teaching me important life lessons. At 6, I went to a large daycare center on Viitantie where my mother also worked. I loved playing at the nearby playground with my friends during the summer. The following year, I started first grade at Kiiminkijoki elementary school. Many of my daycare and playground friends also attended and we bonded over learning about computers. Our favorite game was "Save Henrietta," which sparked my interest in technology that continues to this day.

(Education Campus, from year 1993 to year 1996, age 4 - 7) During my early childhood in Kiiminki, education had a strong presence in my life. From ages 4 to 5, I attended daycare in different houses around the local area and formed friendships with kids my age. I remember the women at these places teaching me important life lessons. At 6, I went to a large daycare center on Viitantie where my mother also worked. I loved playing at the nearby playground with my friends during the summer. The following year, I started first grade at Kiiminkijoki elementary school. Many of my daycare and playground friends also attended and we bonded over learning about computers. Our favorite game was "Save Henrietta," which sparked my interest in technology that continues to this day.

At the Education Campus in Kiiminki, during second grade in 1997, I continued learning about computers and had a short day on Tuesdays. Gym class was a blast, especially when we went cross-country skiing on the nearby river. In the winter, I even placed second in a skiing competition. I had fun playing with my classmates and joined a classical guitar club. The following year in third grade, soda discos began and my classmates pressured me to dance slow dances with my friend Hanna. Unfortunately, I couldn't enjoy these events due to my difficult home life and lack of support. This eventually led to me being excluded and mistreated by my classmates. Sadly, the effects of this sexual abuse continued to impact my life, causing isolation and discrimination at school.

At ten years old, I started fourth grade at Kiiminkijoki Elementary School, feeling completely isolated due to the sexual harassment I experienced. Despite wanting to join in on football with the other boys, I was excluded and didn't understand why. Things only got worse when my mother intervened, causing even more distress.

But the following year, I transferred to Haukipudas, Kello's elementary school in Class 5C. The move came with my mother's new boyfriend, and though I was reluctant to leave Kiiminki, the atmosphere at my new school was refreshing. The students were more easygoing and less competitive, though still athletic.

During my time at Kiiminki's Education Campus, from 1997 to 2000, I experienced both joy and pain. In second grade, I continued to learn about computers and had fun with cross-country skiing in gym class. However, due to a difficult home life, I was excluded and mistreated by my classmates. This continued in third grade, where I felt isolated and pressured to join activities like soda discos, but couldn't fully enjoy them. The next year, I transferred to a new school with my mother's new boyfriend and found a more relaxed atmosphere. Despite still facing discrimination, I was happy to leave behind the competitive environment of my previous school.

At the age of 12, I made the decision to switch schools and joined my sister in attending the Oulu Rudolf Steiner School. While I enjoyed my time there, my curiosity led me to visit on the same day as my sister, and I was immediately sold on the Steiner School's unique and amazing approach to education. We often went on small trips and spent days studying in an old villa surrounded by nature.

The following year, at 13, I started 7th grade at the Steiner school, where I continued to thrive in their unconventional teaching methods. Though I noticed I was behind in traditional subjects like Finnish and math, I was more interested in the larger world views and discussions we had. However, I did sometimes feel frustrated by the conservative atmosphere and lack of girls to socialize with during my free time, and I longed to start dating. Looking back, I do not regret my decision to switch to the Steiner school and have fond memories of the unique experiences I had there.

Educational Years at Oulu Steiner School, 2003-2004:
In my 8th and 9th grade years at Oulu Steiner School, I had a lot of fun. My classmates were interesting and we did exciting things together. However, I was disappointed by the lack of girls to hang out with during free time, and I wished for more opportunities to socialize. 
But in the spring of 2005, we made the most of our time together by celebrating May Day and the end of school festivities. It was a memorable and enjoyable experience, especially with the warm weather of +20 degrees Celsius.

At the age of 12, I made the decision to switch to Oulu Rudolf Steiner School, joining my sister. The following year, I started 7th grade there and continued to thrive in their unconventional teaching methods. However, the conservative atmosphere and lack of girls to socialize with during free time sometimes left me frustrated. Nonetheless, I have fond memories of the unique experiences and discussions we had, and I do not regret my decision to switch schools. My 8th and 9th grade years were filled with fun experiences and interesting classmates, but I longed for more opportunities to socialize with girls. We made the most of our time together, especially during the spring festivities and warm weather.

From the ages of 8 to 15, my time at Kiiminki's Education Campus and Oulu Rudolf Steiner School was filled with a mix of joy and pain. In second grade, I had fun learning about computers and skiing in gym class, but faced exclusion and mistreatment from my classmates due to a difficult home life. This continued in third grade but I found a more relaxed atmosphere when I transferred to a new school the following year. However, despite still facing discrimination, I was happy to leave behind the competitive environment of my previous school. At the age of 12, I switched to Oulu Rudolf Steiner School and found their unconventional teaching methods to be a good fit for me. However, I sometimes felt frustrated by the conservative atmosphere and lack of girls to socialize with. But overall, I have fond memories of my time there and do not regret my decision. My 8th and 9th grade years were filled with fun experiences and interesting classmates, but I longed for more opportunities to socialize with girls. Despite this, we made the most of our time together, especially during spring festivities and warm weather.

My early childhood in Kiiminki was heavily influenced by education. From ages 4 to 5, I attended daycare and learned important life lessons from the women there. At 6, I started attending a large daycare center and spent my summers playing at the nearby playground with friends. The following year, I began first grade at Kiiminkijoki elementary school. Many of my daycare and playground friends also attended, and we bonded over learning about computers. This sparked my interest in technology. From ages 8 to 15, my time at Kiiminki's Education Campus and Oulu Rudolf Steiner School was a mix of joy and pain. I switched schools in third grade, but still faced discrimination. At 12, I transferred to Oulu Rudolf Steiner School and found their unconventional teaching methods a good fit. Despite some frustrations, I have fond memories of my time there. My 8th and 9th grade years were filled with fun experiences and interesting classmates, but I longed for more opportunities to socialize with girls. Overall, education has played a significant role in shaping my early years.

In 2005, at age 16, I started my first year at Tampere Rudolf Steiner High School in Oulu. My friends from Haukipudas and Kello Kiviniemi influenced me to consider transferring to Oulu Normal School's high school program, but I ultimately stayed at the Steiner School. However, the addition of new students from state schools changed the dynamics, making me feel like I didn't belong to either group. In 2006, at age 17, I started my second year. While school was still enjoyable, the arrival of my girlfriend from online and classmates from other schools caused some difficulties. The sense of community between the original students and the new ones was not as strong as I had hoped, with the newcomers bringing in cynicism. Overall, my four years at the Steiner school greatly influenced my thinking.

In 2007, I was attending Tampereen Rudolf Steiner High School's Oulu branch for my third year of high school. It was a unique experience with many artistic projects, but overall enjoyable. Thankfully, a girl I had met online switched schools. The following year, as a 19-year-old, I continued at the Oulu branch for my extra class, which was equivalent to the 3rd grade in regular high schools. We worked hard for the national matriculation exams and the atmosphere was more focused and "normal."

During my time at Tampere Rudolf Steiner High School's Oulu branch, from 2005 to 2008, I experienced significant changes and challenges. In my first two years, from age 16 to 17, I struggled to find my place among new students from different schools. However, I also formed a strong bond with my girlfriend who transferred to the school. In my last two years, at ages 18 and 19, I continued to thrive in the unique and artistic environment, while also preparing for my national exams. Despite the challenges, my time at the Steiner school greatly influenced my thinking.

In 2009, at the age of 20, I joined the Finnish Defence Forces at the Lapland Air Command in Rovaniemi. I spent a year serving in the army, attending non-commissioned officer school for leadership training and leading a military police squad for six months. The following year, at 21, I began studying electrical engineering at the University of Vaasa, but later returned to Oulu due to my poor health after completing the army.

Education Campus, 2011-2012

During my time at the University of Oulu studying Environmental Engineering, my health was in a weak state due to my time in the army. As a result, I was unable to fully participate in social events and struggled to make connections with my classmates. Despite this, I remained determined to continue my studies and work towards my goals.

From 2009-2010, at the age of 20-21, I joined the Finnish Defence Forces at the Lapland Air Command and attended non-commissioned officer school for leadership training. I also led a military police squad for six months. Due to my health, I returned to Oulu after completing my service and began studying electrical engineering at the University of Vaasa. The following year, at 22, I switched to the University of Oulu to pursue Environmental Engineering. Despite my struggles with health and social connections, I remained determined to achieve my goals.

During my education years, from 2005 to 2012, I faced various challenges and changes while pursuing my academic goals. At the Tampere Rudolf Steiner High School's Oulu branch from 2005 to 2008, I struggled to fit in but also formed a strong bond with my girlfriend. However, my last two years there were more successful as I prepared for my national exams. After a brief stint in the Finnish Defence Forces from 2009-2010, I returned to Oulu to study electrical engineering at the University of Vaasa at the age of 22. My determination to achieve my goals led me to switch to Environmental Engineering at the University of Oulu, despite facing health and social struggles. Overall, my time at the Steiner school greatly influenced my thinking.

In 2013, at the age of 24, I enrolled at the University of Oulu to study environmental engineering. However, my health was poor after serving in the military and my studies suffered as a result. I also couldn't attend any student events. Realizing that I needed a change, I started considering a different field.

The following year, at 25, I remained at the University of Oulu for environmental engineering but my health continued to impact my studies. Unable to attend student events, I decided to start taking computer science courses while still in the environmental engineering program. Despite facing more challenges in the environmental engineering program, I was determined to explore my interest in computer science.

In 2015 and 2016, at the age of 26 and 27 respectively, I attended the University of Oulu for information technology. Despite struggling with my health after finishing my military service, I found some success in my studies. However, I still had difficulty with social events and preferred to focus on the technical aspects of my education.

At 24, I started studying environmental engineering at the University of Oulu, but my health suffered from my military service and I struggled to keep up with my studies. In 2015 and 2016, now 26 and 27, I switched to studying information technology, finding more success, although my health still challenged my ability to attend social events. Alongside my environmental engineering studies, I also began taking computer science courses, determined to pursue my interest in the field.

In 2017, at the age of 28, I attended the Education Campus at the University of Oulu in the field of Information Technology. Despite my continued poor health following my time in the army, my studies began to improve. However, I still struggled with attending student events, preferring to focus on my studies in IT. This trend continued into 2018 when I was 29 years old.

(Education Campus, from year 2017 to year 2018, age 28 - 29) In 2017, at the age of 28, I attended the Education Campus at the University of Oulu in the field of Information Technology. Despite my continued poor health following my time in the army, my studies began to improve. However, I still struggled with attending student events, preferring to focus on my studies in IT. This trend continued into 2018 when I was 29 years old.

From 2013 to 2016, from ages 24 to 27, I studied environmental engineering at the University of Oulu, but my health declined due to military service, affecting my studies. At 26 and 27, I switched to information technology and also began taking computer science courses. From 2017 to 2018, at ages 28 and 29, I attended the Education Campus at the same university, where my health improved but I preferred to focus on my IT studies rather than attending social events.

During my education years, from 2005 to 2012, I faced various challenges and changes while pursuing my academic goals. At the Tampere Rudolf Steiner High School's Oulu branch, I struggled to fit in but also formed a strong bond with my girlfriend. However, my last two years there were more successful as I prepared for my national exams. After a brief stint in the Finnish Defence Forces, I returned to Oulu to study electrical engineering at the University of Vaasa. But my determination to achieve my goals led me to switch to Environmental Engineering at the University of Oulu, despite facing health and social struggles. My time at the Steiner school greatly influenced my thinking. From 2013 to 2016, I continued my studies in environmental engineering, but my health declined due to military service. Eventually, I switched to information technology and began taking computer science courses. Later, I attended the Education Campus at the University of Oulu from 2017 to 2018, where my health improved. However, I chose to focus on my IT studies rather than attending social events.

From my early childhood in Kiiminki to my education years, my experiences in the Education Campus have heavily influenced my growth and development. Starting from ages 4 to 15, I attended daycare and elementary school, where I formed friendships and developed a passion for technology. Although I faced some discrimination during this time, I eventually found a good fit in Oulu Rudolf Steiner School. From 16 to 31, I faced various challenges and changes while pursuing my academic goals at different schools, including a brief stint in the Finnish Defence Forces. My determination to achieve my goals led me to switch majors and ultimately focus on information technology. Throughout my educational journey, I have been influenced by the unconventional teaching methods at the Steiner school and the opportunity to improve my health at the Education Campus at the University of Oulu. Despite facing some struggles, education has played a significant role in shaping who I am today.
(Education Campus, year 2021, age 32) OAMK, education for the unemployed

In 2023, at the age of 34, I enrolled in a Professional Music Producer Diploma program at the Education Campus in Lapland's Music House. After a year and a half of studying, my journey continued in 2024 as I pursued a Professional Music Producer Degree at Lappia Music House in Tornio. By June of that year, I successfully completed my studies at the age of 35.

In 2021, at the age of 32, I attended OAMK's Education Campus for unemployed individuals. My educational pursuits continued in 2023, as I enrolled in a Professional Music Producer Diploma program at the Education Campus in Lapland's Music House. This led me to pursue a Professional Music Producer Degree at Lappia Music House in Tornio in 2024, at the age of 34. After completing my studies in 1 year and 6 months, I graduated at the age of 35 in June of the same year.

Siivosin äidin mukana asuntoa, ja oma huone piti siivota. Siivoamiseen kuului aina imurointi, pintojen luutuaminen, ja joskus jopa lattian luutuaminen.
Nautin melko paljon siisteydestä ja pölyjen pyyhkimisestä.
Siivoaminen oli aina melko kevyt kehoitus, ja vähintään puolet ajasta tein sen vapaaehtoisesti.

Meillä oli kotona pientä lautatavaraa, saha, vasaroita ja nauloja.
Saimme värkätä niillä mitä halusimme, ja mehän paukutimme nauloja lautoihin.

Olin myös ylpeä pyörästäni, ja pesin sitä lämpimillä ilmoilla aina silloin tällöin vesisankon ja luudun kanssa.
years.text:
I helped my mother clean up the apartment, and I had to clean my own room. Cleaning always involved vacuuming, wiping surfaces, and sometimes even mopping the floor.
I quite enjoyed the tidiness and dusting.
Cleaning was always a fairly light task, and at least half of the time I did it voluntarily.

We had some small lumber at home, a saw, hammers and nails.
We got to tinker with them however we wanted, and we often hammered nails into boards.

I was also proud of my bike, and on warm days I would wash it with a bucket of water and a mop.

years.native_text:
Voin huonosti Kiiminkijoen ala-asteella rakennuksen homeongelmien takia. Homeongelmaa ja minun terveysongelmia ei tunnustettu, vaan minua jopa pidettiin pilkkanani.

Usein kesken koulutuntien, sain pitkiä kohtauksia, kun silmäni vuosivat vettä niin paljon, etten voinut katsoa taululle.
Kyse ei ollut mistään tunteisiin liittyvästä, mutta epäilen että luokkakaverini pitivät sitä mahdollisena, mikä pahensi entisestään heidän ikävää käytöstään minua kohtaan.
years.text:
I was feeling really bad at the Kiiminkijoki elementary school due to the building's mold problems. The mold issue and my health problems were not acknowledged, but instead ridiculed.

During school hours, I often experienced long bouts where my eyes would water so much that I couldn't even look at the board.
It wasn't anything related to emotions, but I suspect my classmates thought it was possible, which only worsened their unpleasant behavior towards me.

years.native_text:
Tyttöystävälläni on pahoja mielenterveysongelmia, ja joudun pelastamaan hänet itsemurhan yrittämiseltä melkein 10 kertaa, mikä vaikuttaa omaan terveyteeni negatiivisesti (mitä en uskonut).
Tämä tapahtumien sarja aiheuttaa myös uuden tapahtumasarjan, missä tyttöystäväni valehtelee ja mustamaalaa minut raiskaajaksi.

Tyttöystäväni oli löytänyt uudesta koulustaan Oulun Lyseon lukiosta huumeidenkäyttäjä-kavereita, joilta hän sai kaikenlaisia huumeita ilmaiseksi.
Hän kävi käyttämässä huumeita Oulun keskustassa, ja tuli sitten minun luo, josta hänen vanhempansa hakivat minut, jotta hän ei jäisi kiinni.
Olin kieltänyt häntä tekemästä niin, ja kerran, kun vastustin hänen toimintaansa voimakkaasti, hän mustamaalasi minut seksuaalisesti ahdistelleet häntä täysin ilman perusteitta.
Hän tiesi, minkälaista voimaa hänen tekstinsä sisälsivät, koska hän oli päiväkirjan kirjoittaja, ja huumehöyryissään hän piti ajatustaan valehdella hyvänä.

Tämä tapahtuma aiheutti hirvittävän kamalan tapahtumasarjan, josta minulla ei ollut mitään hajua, missä tyttöystäväni valheellisesti väitti minua käytännössä raiskaajaksi.
years.text:
My girlfriend has severe mental health issues and I have had to save her from attempting suicide almost 10 times, which has negatively affected my own well-being (something I never thought would happen).
This series of events has also led to a new series of incidents where my girlfriend lies and paints me as a rapist.

My girlfriend had found new friends at her new school, Oulun Lyseo High School, who were drug users and were giving her all kinds of drugs for free.
She would go and use drugs in the city center of Oulu, and then come to my place, where her parents would pick me up so she wouldn't get caught.
I had forbidden her from doing so, and one time when I strongly opposed her actions, she falsely accused me of sexually assaulting her without any reason.
She knew the power of her words, as she was a diary writer and in her drug-induced state, she saw lying as a good thing.

This event triggered a terrifying series of events, of which I had no idea, where my girlfriend falsely claimed that I was essentially a rapist.

years.native_text:
Tapahtuu outo tapahtumasarja, jolloin minut pahoinpidellään vakavasti.
Vappu-aattona olemme viettämässä iltaa Oulun torinrannassa.
Exäni on paikalla ja hän käy kääntymässä vihaisena sanaakaan sanomatta minun kaveriporukkani luona.
En ymmärtänyt asiasta mitään, enkä pitänyt sitä minään, koska exälläni ei ole yhtäkään todellista syystä olla minulle vihainen.
Käyn välissä kotona jostain syystä, mutta päätän lähtä takaisin, koska en näe mitään syytä jäädä kotiin.
Tulee ilta, klo21, ja porukkamme päättää lähteä baariin.
Huomaan, että pyöräni jäi torinrantaan, ja käsken kavereitani odottaa, että haen sen, mutta he eivät odota.
Mietin, että haen pyörän ja menen heidän peräänsä.

Kun avaan pyörääni, niin 3 miestä hyökkää kimppuuni selän takaa provosoimatta.
Muistan vain nähneeni miehet ennen lukon ääreen menemistä.
Olin erittäin humalassa.
Muistan miesten huutaneen minulle jotain, minkä jälkeenpäin tulkitsin ulkomaalaiseksi kieleksi, mutta mikä saattoi olla myös Suomea.
Käännyn huutajien puoleen, ja samalla näen minun pääni suuntaan liikkuvan olutpullon.
Koska ehdin nähdä ja ymmärtää lähestyvän pullon, niin ehdin sulkea silmäni lujasti ja kääntää päätäni.
Lasinen pullo osuu oikealle puolelle otsaani pirstoutuen.
Lähden juoksemaan välittömästi.
Soitan välittömästi 112:seen.
Ironista kyllä, alle sadan metrin päässä on ambulanssi, koska oli vappu.
Menen kolkuttamaan ambulanssin ikkunaa, ja hetken minua katsottuaan he ottavat minut ambulanssin sisään.
He paketoivat pääni siteillä, ja kuskaavat meidät sairaalaan melko pian.

Käyn tekemässä seuraavana päivänä rikosilmoituksen poliisiasemalla, mutta olin täysin ymmärämätön tilanteen suhteen.
Vielä tänäkin päivänä voin vain spekuloida, että ketä he olivat, ja miksi he tekivät mitä tekivät.
Todenäköisenä pidetään ulkomaalaisten väkivallantekoa huonoista syistä paikallisia kohtaan, mutta itse pidän todennäköisempänä exäni huumekavereita.

Exäni huumekaverit olivat myös vahvasti Kokoomus-puoluelaisten lapsia ja Kokoomusnuorten ympärillä pyöriviä ihmisiä.
years.text:
A strange series of events occurs, where I am severely assaulted.
On the eve of May Day, we are celebrating the evening at the Oulu market square.
My ex is there and he passes by my friend group with anger, not saying a word to me.
I didn't understand anything about it, and I didn't think much of it, because my ex has no real reason to be angry with me.
I take a break at home for some reason, but I decide to go back because I don't see any reason to stay at home.
The evening comes, at 9 pm, and our group decides to go to a bar.
I notice that my bike was left at the market square, and I ask my friends to wait for me to get it, but they don't wait.
I think about picking up my bike and following them.

As I unlock my bike, 3 men attack me from behind without provocation.
I only remember seeing the men before going to the bike lock.
I was very drunk.
I remember the men shouting something at me, which I later interpret as a foreign language, but it could have also been Finnish.
I turn to face the shouters, and at the same time I see a beer bottle moving towards my head.
Because I have time to see and understand the approaching bottle, I quickly close my eyes and turn my head.
The glass bottle hits the right side of my forehead and shatters.
I immediately start running.
I immediately call 112.
Ironically, there is an ambulance less than a hundred meters away because it was May Day.
I knock on the ambulance window, and after looking at me for a moment, they take me inside the ambulance.
They wrap my head with bandages and take us to the hospital fairly quickly.

I go to the police station the next day to file a report, but I was completely unaware of the situation.
Even to this day, I can only speculate who they were and why they did what they did.
It is believed that they were foreign individuals who commit acts of violence against locals for no good reason, but I personally believe that my ex's friends involved in drugs are more likely suspects.

My ex's drug friends were also heavily involved with children of members of the Kokoomus party and people revolving around the Young Finns Party.

It becomes clear that her lies had caused a terrible amount of dangerous situations and mistreatment towards me, even putting me in life-threatening situations.

value.text: I was only 2 years old when my parents got divorced and I have no memories of them being together. My father and I continued to have a relationship, with me visiting him every other weekend, until I became an adult. During this time, he started dating a new girlfriend who was in his life until her passing in 2008.

(Family Parental, from year 1991 to year 1992, age 2 - 3) I was only 2 years old when my parents got divorced and I have no memories of them being together. My father and I continued to have a relationship, with me visiting him every other weekend, until I became an adult. During this time, he started dating a new girlfriend who was in his life until her passing in 2008.

At the age of 4 and 5, I had a busy schedule visiting both sets of grandparents. I would spend one or two nights at my maternal grandmother's house in Karjasilta, Oulu, almost twice a month. On the weekends I didn't visit my grandmother, I would go to my father's house and also stop by my grandparents' on his side. My mother and I also made separate trips to her parents' house.

As a young child, I spent time with both sides of my family. Every other weekend, I visited my father and often saw my grandparents on his side. Similarly, my mother and I would visit her parents' house separately.

At ages 4 to 7, I had a busy schedule visiting both sets of grandparents. Every other weekend, I would spend one or two nights at my maternal grandmother's house in Oulu. On the weekends I didn't visit her, I would see my father's parents and also visit my father's house. My mother and I also made separate trips to her parents' house.

I had a busy childhood, split between my divorced parents. From ages 0-3, I only saw my father every other weekend and he had a new girlfriend until her passing in 2008. From ages 4-7, I had a jam-packed schedule, alternating between visits to my maternal grandmother in Oulu and trips to see both sets of grandparents. My mother and I also made separate trips to her parents' house.

During the summers, we visit my paternal grandmother's childhood home, a large farm in Pudasjärvi, with my cousins and whole family. My dad, sister, grandpa and grandma join us, along with visitors who often come by car.
Every other weekend, I visit my father and often my grandparents on his side. I also go separately with my mother to her parents' house.
As a child of divorced parents, I split my time between my father's house every other weekend and my mother's parents' house separately. My paternal grandparents were also a part of these visits.

Growing up with divorced parents meant dividing my time between different homes. During the summers, my extended family would gather at my paternal grandmother's farm in Pudasjärvi, with visits from other relatives. Every other weekend, I would alternate between staying with my father and visiting my grandparents on his side. Similarly, I would spend time with my mother and her parents on separate occasions.
When I was 12 and 13, I visited my father every other weekend, along with my grandparents on his side. I also went separately with my mother to her parents' house.
In middle school, I spent my weekends visiting my father and my grandparents on his side, while also making trips to my mother's parents' house separately with her.

During my early teenage years, I split my time between visiting my father and grandparents on his side every other weekend, and going to my mother's parents' house separately. This continued throughout middle school until I reached the age of 15.

Growing up with divorced parents, I split my time between different homes and extended family gatherings at my paternal grandmother's farm in Pudasjärvi. Every other weekend, I alternated between staying with my father and visiting my grandparents. This continued throughout my middle school years, until I turned 15.

Growing up in a divorced household, my childhood was split between two different homes and extended family gatherings. From ages 0-7, I spent every other weekend with my father and also visited my maternal grandmother in Oulu and my mother's parents separately. This busy schedule continued from ages 8-15, with alternating visits to my father's and grandfather's farm in Pudasjärvi. By the time I turned 15, this routine had become a familiar part of my life.
In 2005 and 2006, at ages 16 and 17, I spent weekends with my father and often visited his parents. Similarly, I also visited my mother's parents separately.

In 2007, at 18 years old, I visited my father and grandparents once every 1-3 months. The following year, my father's longtime girlfriend and wife Pirjo Savilampi passed away from cancer, and I continued to visit them at the same frequency.

From 2005 to 2006, between the ages of 16 and 17, I spent weekends with my father and visited my grandparents on both sides. This continued when I turned 18 in 2007, however, in the following year my dad's wife passed away and I continued to visit them once every 1-3 months.

In 2009, at the age of 20, I joined the army and rarely saw my relatives. Living in a bustling city, I longed for the tranquility of the countryside. After serving in the army, I became weak and was unable to visit my relatives as often. What made it even more conflicting was that they supported the torture of the army.

After completing my time in the army, I found myself physically and emotionally drained. As a result, I wasn't able to visit my relatives as frequently as before. This was made even more complicated by the fact that they supported my decision to join the army, despite the difficulties and challenges I faced during my service. It's a conflicting feeling that I'm still trying to understand.

Between 2009 and 2012, age 20-23, I experienced a deep conflict between my family and my army service. Yearning for the peace of the countryside, I rarely saw my relatives while in the bustling city. And even after completing my time in the army, my visits were limited due to physical and emotional exhaustion. What added to the complexity was that my family supported my decision to join the army, despite the difficulties I faced. It's a feeling that I'm still trying to navigate.

From 2005 to 2006, ages 16-17, I spent weekends with my dad and visited both sets of grandparents. This continued when I turned 18 in 2007, but my dad's wife passing away changed things. I visited them once every 1-3 months until 2008, ages 20-23, when my army service caused a deep conflict with my family. In the bustling city, I rarely saw them and even after completing my service, exhaustion limited my visits. What added to the complexity was that my family supported my decision to join the army. I'm still navigating these feelings.

After my time in the army, I am physically and emotionally drained. This means I am unable to visit my relatives as often as I used to. It is difficult for me since they too supported my military service, which brings about conflicting emotions.
After finishing my time in the army, I became weaker and couldn't visit my relatives as often. It was a conflicting feeling knowing that they supported the torture that came with serving.

During and after my time in the army, I struggled to maintain a close relationship with my relatives. The physical and emotional toll of my service made it difficult to visit them as often as I used to, and it was conflicting to know that they had supported my decision to serve despite the challenges it brought.

In 2017, after serving in the army, I found myself unable to visit my relatives as often as I used to. What made it even harder was knowing that they had supported the army's tactics, leaving me feeling conflicted. And as if that wasn't enough, in 2018, both my grandfather and grandmother on my father's side passed away within a short time of each other.
In 2019 and 2020, at age 30 and 31, I rarely visit my father and mother separately, as well as my maternal grandparents' home.

In the span of three years, from ages 28 to 31, I found myself drifting away from my extended family. After leaving the army in 2017, I struggled to maintain contact with relatives who had supported the army's tactics. The passing of my grandfather and grandmother in 2018 only added to the strain. Things didn't improve in the following years as my visits to my parents and maternal grandparents became infrequent.

During and after my time in the army, I struggled to maintain a close relationship with my extended family. The physical and emotional toll of my service made it difficult to visit them regularly, despite their initial support for my decision to serve. However, as I left the army and years passed, the strain on our relationships only grew. The passing of my grandparents in 2018 further weighed on our dwindling family ties. My visits to my parents and maternal grandparents became infrequent, as I found myself drifting away from my extended family.

From 2005 to 2020, I navigated complex relationships with my extended family, particularly with my parents, during my late teenage years into my adult life. After my dad's wife passed away in 2007, I visited them once every few months until my military service caused a deep conflict in 2008. Despite their initial support, the toll of my service made visiting difficult and strained our relationships. As the years passed and my grandparents passed away, my visits became more infrequent and I drifted away from my extended family.

Growing up in a divorced household, my childhood was split between two different homes and extended family gatherings. From ages 0-7, I spent every other weekend with my father and also visited my maternal grandmother in Oulu and my mother's parents separately. This busy schedule continued from ages 8-15, with alternating visits to my father's and grandfather's farm in Pudasjärvi. By the time I turned 15, this routine had become a familiar part of my life. However, as I entered my late teenage years and into adulthood, the complex relationships within my extended family became a source of conflict and distance. Despite initially visiting my father and stepmother once every few months, our relationship strained due to my military service in 2008 and the loss of my grandparents. As a result, my visits to them became more infrequent and I drifted away from my extended family.

In 2021, at age 32, I infrequently visit my parents separately and rarely visit my mother's parents. But by 2022, at age 33, our relationship has worsened, straining my visits to my mother and her parents.

In 2023, at 34 years old, I don't often visit my parents or my mother's side of the family separately. Our strained relationship is due to her mean nature. However, in 2024 at 35 years old, my grandfather from my mother's side passes away at 90. I make an effort to visit my grandmother and spend time with her. Despite my continued disconnection with my mother, I do my best to offer her companionship and support during this difficult time.

From 2021 to 2022, at ages 32 to 33, my relationship with my parents and mother's parents has deteriorated. By 2022, our strained relationship has caused me to rarely visit my mother and her parents. 
From 2023 to 2024, at ages 34 to 35, my relationship with my mother remains tense due to her mean nature. However, when my 90-year-old grandfather passes away in 2024, I make an effort to reconnect with my grandmother and offer her companionship and support amidst our continued disconnect.

years.native_text:
Kiimingissä oli urheilukilpailuja, joissa kävin katsomassa. Kävin pesäpallo-otteluissa. Koulussamme oli yleisurheilukilpailut, joihin osallistuin mielellään.

Olin yötä serkkujeni luona muutaman kerran vuodesta, ja kesällä otimme 2 skeittilautaa, ja lähdimme rullaamaan ympäri naapurustoa lauantai- ja sunnuntaiaamuisin.
years.text:
There were sports competitions in Kiimingi, which I went to watch. I went to baseball games. Our school had track and field competitions, which I gladly participated in.

I stayed overnight at my cousins' house a few times a year, and in the summer we took 2 skateboards and went skating around the neighborhood on Saturday and Sunday mornings.

Personal Taste Books, year 1993-1994, age 4-5: Children's Books
FI-FI: Urheilu
EN-US: Sports

During my early childhood, between the ages of 6 and 7 in 1995 and 1996, my personal taste in books focused on children's literature. I discovered a treasure trove of old Uncle Scrooge comics at my grandmother's house, which I devoured. The following year, at age 7, I continued my love for comics by borrowing them from the library, including Tintin, Asterix, Garfield, Calvin & Hobbes, and Donald Duck. I also dabbled in reading easy novels as my love for books grew.

From 1993 to 1994, during the ages of 4 and 5, I gravitated towards children's books and developed a fondness for sports literature. This interest continued into 1995 and 1996 when I was 6 and 7 years old and discovered a love for comics, specifically Uncle Scrooge, Tintin, Asterix, Garfield, Calvin & Hobbes, and Donald Duck. As my passion for books grew, I also began exploring easy novels.

As my passion for books grew, I also began exploring easy novels.

During the ages of 8 and 9, I was an avid reader of Donald Duck comics and often borrowed them from the library. I also enjoyed other comics such as Tintin, Asterix, Garfield, and Calvin & Hobbes. In addition to comics, I read easy novels during this time.

During my younger years at the age of 10 and 11, my love for reading was evident through my choice of books. I was a huge fan of comics such as Donald Duck, Tintin, Asterix, Garfield, Calvin & Hobbes, and Uncle Scrooge. I borrowed them from the library and also enjoyed reading easy novels. As I grew older, my taste in reading remained similar as I still enjoyed comics and easy novels, along with reading articles from the internet.

I was a big fan of popular series such as Donald Duck, Tintin, Asterix, Garfield, Calvin & Hobbes, and Uncle Scrooge, borrowing them from the library and enjoying them repeatedly. As I grew older, my love for comics and literature remained strong, as I often read articles from the internet as well.

In 2001, my library changed to the Oulu City Library, opening up a whole new world of books for 12-year-old me. I devoured quirky comics and novels borrowed from the library, as well as reading various English texts online. After school, I made a pit stop at Tuiran Library to peruse monthly technical and scientific magazines. By the following year, I had developed a strong personal taste in literature and continued to frequent the Oulu City Library, along with my regular visit to Tuiran Library after school.

In 2003 and 2004, at the age of 14 and 15, respectively, I had a voracious appetite for reading. From quirky comics to thought-provoking novels, I often found myself borrowing books from the Oulu City Library. I also spent a lot of time reading English texts on the Internet. After school, I would make a pit stop at the Tuiran Library, where I could dive into monthly technical and scientific magazines. My love for reading only grew with each passing year.

As I grew older, my love for comics and literature remained strong, and I also enjoyed reading articles and English texts online. My love for reading continued to grow as I got older.

My love for comics and novels remained strong as I matured, and I also enjoyed reading online articles and texts. During my teenage years, I was an avid reader. I would often borrow novels from the Oulu City Library and stop by the Tuiran Library after school to read technical and scientific magazines.

Personal Taste Books, 2007-2008, ages 18-19:
I visit Oulu City Library for my interests in both music and literature. At the music department, I devour English music magazines, while also borrowing compelling novels to read. On my way home from school, I make a pit stop at Tuiran Library to immerse myself in monthly technical and scientific publications. This ritual continues in the following year, where I continue to indulge in music and novels through the city library.

During my teenage years, I was a frequent visitor of the Oulu City and Tuiran Libraries. I would devour English music magazines and compelling novels at the city library, while also stopping by the Tuiran Library to read technical and scientific publications. This ritual continued into my late teens, as I fed my interests in both music and literature through the city library.

value.text: At the young age of 4 and 5, I loved spending time with friends and engaging in imaginative play. Whether it was playing board games or coming up with creative scenarios together, we always had a great time. My friend Olli-Pekka's 386 DOS PC and its games also captivated me, and I enjoyed watching children's TV shows as well. Overall, I had a diverse taste in entertainment, but my love for playing with friends remained constant.

At age 6 and 7, my personal taste in entertainment revolved around games and technology. I loved playing games on my friend's DOS PC and Amiga 500, and watching children's TV shows. Even at daycare, I couldn't resist playing on the computer. But I also enjoyed classic forms of entertainment, such as board games and imaginative play with friends. Going to the movies and visiting Oulu's science center, Tietomaa, were special treats. And who could forget my love for The Smurfs dance music records for kids? Overall, I was drawn to activities that were fun, creative, and interactive.

Overall, my taste in entertainment revolved around interactive, creative, and fun activities.

Personal Taste Entertainment, years 1997-1998, ages 8-9:

I loved watching TV shows and playing games on my Amiga 500 as a kid. My friends and I also enjoyed playing board games and using our imaginations together. Going to the movies and visiting Oulu's City Science Centre Tietoma were rare but exciting treats.

My friend Olli-Pekka's satellite TV introduced me to Music TV and Cartoon Network and I couldn't get enough. I also loved dancing to the Smurfs' music albums made for kids.

By the time I turned 9, I had expanded my interests to include watching both children's programs and regular TV shows. I also started playing DOS and Windows games. Going to the movies and visiting Tietomaa remained fun experiences for me.

My friend's satellite TV continued to entertain me with Music TV, Cartoon Network, and the hit show Friends. I also enjoyed borrowing regular music from the library and listening to the radio.

Overall, my personal entertainment tastes from 1997 to 1998 revolved around TV, games, and music, with occasional trips to the movies and the science center.

From watching TV shows for children and regular programs to playing games on my Amiga 500 and DOS and Windows games, I was always entertained. Music was a big part of my entertainment, whether it was listening to Smurfs dance music CDs or borrowing regular music CDs from the library. I also enjoyed listening to the radio and browsing the internet. As I grew older, my interests expanded to include Formula 1 races, PlayStation games, and playing PC games against friends.

years.keywords: k modem, Fixed Internet connection, News websites, Forum websites, English forums, Finnish forums, Neutral opinion, Old friends, Acquaintances, Kiimingi, Sad environment, Single mother, Older sister, Humor, Different places, Unique communities, Friendly visitor, Home
years.native_text:
Kotiimme tulee kiinteä Internet-yhteys, kun tähän asti käytin kotona 56k-modeemia. Käytän massiivisesti enemmän aikaa uutis- ja foorumisivustoilla.
Luen tosi paljon foorumeita, mutta en puhu mitään siellä, koska en keksi mitä sanoa.
Itseasiassa kirjoitan jonkun verran englanninkielisille foorumeille, mutta en suomenkielisille.

Minulla on neutraali mielipide ihmisten suhteen.

Vanhat kaverini ja tuttuni irkkasivat paljon Kiimingissä.
He eivät olleet lämpimiä minun puheelleni ollenkaan.
Luultavasti syynä oli se, että olin kasvanut melko surullisissa oloissa yksinhuoltaja äitini ja iso-siskoni kanssa, eikä elämässä ollut huumoria.
Eri paikkakunnan ihmiset toimivat todella eri tavalla, mikä opetti minulle selvästi sen, että täällä on hyvin ainutlaatuisia isoja yhteisöjä, jotka eivät ole edes tietoisia itsestään.
Totesin oman paikkani olevan näiden yhteisöjen välissä, ja minun rooli on olla ystävällinen vierailija yhteisöissä, koska en kokenut niitä yhteisöjä kodikseni.
years.text:
Our home is getting a fixed Internet connection, as until now I've been using a 56k modem at home. I spend significantly more time on news and forum websites. I read a lot of forums, but I don't say anything because I can't come up with anything to say. In fact, I write sometimes on English forums, but not on Finnish ones.

I have a neutral opinion of people.

My old friends and acquaintances used to chat a lot in Kiimingi. They weren't very welcoming towards me. It was probably because I grew up in a rather sad environment with my single mother and older sister, and there wasn't much humor in my life. People from different places act very differently, which taught me that there are truly unique, large communities here that aren't even aware of themselves. I realized that I fit in between these communities, and my role is to be a friendly visitor in them, as I didn't feel like those communities were my home.

years.native_text:
Lukion valitseminen painosti miettimään asioita isossa mittakaavassa ja omaa paikkaansa siinä.
Olin pettynyt pahasti varhaisimpiin kavereihini, ja jonkin verran myös toiseksi vanhimman koulun kavereihini, mutta halusin kuulua joukkoon.
Minun oli vaikea valita, että voin paremmin Steinerkoulun kautta tulevassa yhteisössä, ja että ihmiset, joilla oli negatiivinen asenne kouluani kohtaa, eivät ajaneet etuani.
En ymmärtänyt poliittisesti, ketä nämä ihmiset ovat, jotka eivät aja etuani.

Biologia oli yksi tärkeimmistä kouluaineista minulle, ja Lukion biologia opetti minulle paljon maailmasta ja myös sen ongelmista.
years.text:
Choosing a high school made me think about things on a larger scale and my place in it. I was deeply disappointed in my earliest friends, and to some extent, also in my second oldest friends from school, but I wanted to belong. 

It was difficult for me to choose, that I could do better through the Steiner School community and that people with a negative attitude towards my school would not drive my interests. I did not politically understand who these people are who do not drive my interests.

Biology was one of the most important subjects for me, and high school biology taught me a lot about the world and its problems.

I voted for the first time in a Finnish election, and I voted for the Social Democratic Party when I received their pamphlet in my mailbox. My bad neighbor voted for the National Coalition Party and was not very happy. It later turned out that he had already been a really nasty, problem-causing monster towards me.

years.keywords: Sledding, Virpiniemi, Ski jumping, Lost, Forest, Signs, Prohibiting, Hill, Friend, Bad idea, Trampled, Maintenance worker, Yelled, Parents, Tears, Ruined, Enemies, School, Influenced, Change schools
years.native_text:
Erikoista kyllä, olin laskemassa pulkkamäkeä Virpiniemessä, kun eksyimme kaverini kanssa mäkihyppytornille. Tulimme metsän puolelta, emmekä nähneet yhtäkään kieltokylttiä mäenlaskua varten. Kaverini halusi kokeilla, vaikka minä pidin sitä huonona ideana. Hän talsi hyppyrin päällä pilaten sen tamppauksen. Hän laski onnistuneesti alas, mutta sitten joku huoltomies tuli huutamaan meille ja vaati meidän vanhempia paikalle. Puoli-itkuissaan me menimme hänen mukana, kun kaverini äiti tulee paikalle ja huutaa päin naamaa tälle miehelle. Kuulemme myös, kun jotkut tulevat sanomaan, että hyppytorni on pilattu. Saimme outoa kyllä, Virpiniemen mäkihyppääjät vihollisiksemme.
En uskaltanut mennä kouluun muutamaan päivään.
Tämä vaikutti siihen, että halusin vaihtaa koulua pois vapaaehtoisesti.
years.text:
Oddly enough, I was sledding at Virpiniemi when my friend and I got lost and ended up at the ski jumping tower. We came from the forest and didn't see any signs prohibiting sledding on the hill. My friend wanted to try it, even though I thought it was a bad idea. He trampled on top of the jump and successfully slid down, but then a maintenance worker came and yelled at us, demanding our parents to come. We went with him, half in tears, and when my friend's mother arrived she yelled in the man's face. We also heard someone say that the jump had been ruined. Strangely enough, we became enemies with the ski jumpers of Virpiniemi.
I didn't dare go to school for a few days.
This influenced me to want to change schools voluntarily.

Olin rippikoulussa, missä muut olivat paikallisia ja tunsivat toisensa, mutta minä en tuntenut ketään, ja kaikki oli tosi kylmiä ja negatiivisiä minua kohtaan. Ne kaikki jäi todella ikäviksi ihmisiksi minun mielessäni.
Halusin olla kaveri yhden kauniin Anna-Maria Veijon kanssa, ja myös päästä suutelemaankin, mutta hän jäi kylmäksi ja negatiiviseksi, vaikka olimmekin melko hyviä kavereita lopulta.

years.keywords: Ex's, Drug buddies, Army, Hard drugs, New friends, Spread, Horrific, False rumors, Rape, Tower, Barracks, Sarcasm, Garbage, Evil, Conspiracy, Military Police Officer Candidate, Jami Matikainen, Worst enemy, List, Actions.
years.native_text:
Armeijassa oli useita exäni huumekavereiden kavereita.
Olin eronnut eksästäni hänen alkaessa käyttämään kovia huumeita uusien kavereidensa kautta.
He onnistuivat levittämään kauheita perättömiä raiskaus-tornihuhuja minusta.

Yhdessä välissä minulla oli tuvassani tyyppi, joka pilkallisella äänensävyllä toisti joka päivä lausetta "Määpä oon Pakonen kuullut vähän juttua susta", johon minä vastasin "no mitä?", johon hän "enpä kerro".
Olin lopulta täysin kiinnostumaton hänestä, koska en voinut kuvitellakkaan heidän puhuvan sellaista roskaa, mitä lopulta opin heidän puhuneen.
Tämä oli ainoa päivän selkeä pahuus, mikä oli "in your face conspiracy".
Hän kertoi ne huhut muille tuvassa olevilleni, joista kukaan ei kertonut juoruja minulle tai antanut vihjettä, vaikka yksi heistä oli sotilaspoliisi upseerikokelas Jami Matikainen.

Koko tupa miehiä, ja monta muuta tuvallista miehiä, meni suoraan pahimmalle vihollis-listalleni heidän "in your face evil conspiracy" toiminnastaan.
years.text:
There were several of my ex's drug buddies' buddies in the army.
I had broken up with my ex when he started using hard drugs through his new friends.
They managed to spread horrific and false rumors about me being a rape tower.

At one point, I had a guy in my barracks who sarcastically repeated the phrase "I've heard some things about you, Pakonen" every day, to which I replied "well, what?", to which he said "I'm not going to tell you".
I eventually became completely disinterested in him because I couldn't imagine them talking that kind of garbage, which I eventually learned they were.
This was the only clear act of evil that day, the "in your face conspiracy".
He told those rumors to the other men in the barrack, none of whom told me or even hinted at them, despite one of them being Military Police Officer Candidate Jami Matikainen.

The whole barracks, including many other barracks men, went straight to the top of my worst enemy list because of their "in your face evil conspiracy" actions.

Luin internetissä Ior Bock nimisestä henkilöstä, ja löysin häneen liittyvän "Bockin Perheen Saaga" kirjan Oulun kaupungin kirjastosta.
Luin kirjan, enkä voinut uskoa tekstiä todeksi. Se oli kuitenkin hirvittävän mielenkiintoinen.
Kirjassa oli paljon todennäköisiä faktoja, joista en ollut kuullut aikaisemmin, kuten että on perimätietoa ja iso määrä ihmisiä yhteisössä, jotka uskovat perimätiedon totuudenmukaisuuteen.
Yritin samaistua ihmisiin ja heidän uskomukseensa.
Selvästi puhuttua historiaa ei kukaan pitänyt täysin luotettavana, mutta sen kautta välittyi tunteita ja logiikkaa, minkä pohjalla oli tositapahtumat, eikä hulluus tai valhe.
Tämä kirja paljasti vaihtoehtoisen tavan purkaa suomen kieltä, mitä pidin erittäin mielenkiintoisena, vaikka en luottanut siihen.
Ymmärsin tämän kirjan vastustajien olevan systeemisesti ongelmallisia, ja ajatuksellisesti joustamattomia ihmisiä, jotka eivät ansaitse valtaa mediassa tai kasvatuksessa.
years.text:
I read about a person named Ior Bock online and found the book "The Bock Family Saga" related to him at the Oulu City Library.
I read the book and couldn't believe the text was true. However, it was incredibly interesting.
The book contained many probable facts that I had not heard before, such as the existence of oral tradition and a large number of people in the community who believe in its accuracy.
I tried to understand the people and their beliefs.
Clearly, no one considered spoken history to be completely reliable, but it conveyed emotions and logic based on real events, not madness or lies.
This book revealed an alternative way of deciphering the Finnish language, which I found very interesting, even though I didn't fully trust it.
I understood the opponents of this book to be systemically problematic, and ideologically inflexible people who do not deserve power in the media or education.

Se sivusto pilkkasi salaliittoteorioita, ja kärjessä oli Uusi Kronologia.
Pidin itseäni asiaan perehtyneenä, mutta en ollut kuullut Uudesta Kronologiasta koskaan aikaisemmin.
Olin siis vuosia stumbleupon.comia käyttäneenä lukenut kaikki merkittävät salaliittoteoriat ja muutakin asian vierestä.

Kun luin Uuden Kronologian tekstin, olin myyty, vaikkakaan en vahvasti.
Se herätti minussa paljon ajatuksia, jotka jäivät muhimaan päässäni.
Se avasi uusia ikkunoita, joista tulvi valoa sisään ensimmämistä kertaa ikinä.
Pohdin paljon asioita tavalla "jos se on oikeasti silleen, niin se asettaa tämän toisen asian aivan erilaiseen näkökulmaan".
Totesin kirjan olevan vähintään erinomainen uusi perspektiivi ja "ajatusten hieroja".
Tarkistin kirjan esittämiä faktoja, ja löysin kaikki tarvittavat tieteelliset todisteet, enkä löytänyt yhtään varsinaista syytä, miksi väittämät eivät olisi totta.
Tunnistin kirjan vastustajat ongelmallisiksi: he vetosivat auktoriteettiin ja halusivat uskoa uskonnollisia tekstejä todeksi.

The website was mocking conspiracy theories, with New Chronology at the forefront.
I considered myself well-informed on the topic, but had never heard of New Chronology before.
Having used stumbleupon.com for years, I thought I had read all the major conspiracy theories and other related material.

As I read the text on New Chronology, I was intrigued, although not fully convinced.
It sparked a lot of thoughts in my mind, which continued to simmer.
It opened new windows, flooding in light for the first time ever.
I pondered many things in the way of "if it is really true, then it puts this other thing in a completely different perspective."
I concluded that the book was at least an excellent new perspective and "mind massager."
I fact-checked the book's claims and found all the necessary scientific evidence, and could not find any real reason why the claims would not be true.
I recognized the opponents of the book as problematic: they appealed to authority and wanted to believe religious texts as truth.

years.text:
I fully understood that my study fatigue and other problems at the university were most likely an external issue. I began to pass my courses, and I noticed that 75% of students were basically cheating their way through the university by looking at the correct answers from old exams, memorizing them, and then going into the exam where there were only slightly modified questions.

Those who keep this method a secret, rather than common knowledge, are clearly enemies of the system. Unfortunately, I identified the majority of university students as being these type of individuals.

I, myself, passed the same exams in a significantly different way, but still utilizing old exams. I broke down the old exam answers even more carefully and thoroughly into generic solution models. I still noticed that the tasks in the courses at the University of Oulu were highly specialized compared to similar American courses. It was as if the teachers were sabotaging those who were using generic methods, favoring those who looked at old correct answers, because the specifically broken-down generic solution model struggled in Finnish exam tasks.

I identified this trend of teachers and students as cheaters, and scientific cheaters at that. They are inclined to please the sponsor of scientific research dishonestly. They support dishonesty in politics and research, which distort the general understanding. They are a truly great systemic actor of evil.
